  "response": "No, vegetarians do not eat fish. The vegetarian diet typically excludes all types of meat, including fish, poultry, and red meat. Vegetarians primarily consume plant-based foods such as fruits, vegetables, grains, legumes, nuts, and seeds. Some vegetarians include dairy products and eggs in their diet, depending on the specific type of vegetarianism they follow.\n\nHowever, there is a dietary category called **pescatarians**, who do eat fish and seafood but avoid other types of meat. They are not considered vegetarians. If someone includes fish in their diet, they should identify as pescatarian rather than vegetarian.",
